Azure provides multiple application hosting options, each suited for different workloads, levels of control, and scalability requirements.

Common hosting options include:

* Virtual Machines (IaaS): Full control over OS and environment
* Azure App Service (PaaS): Managed platform for web apps and APIs
* Containers (ACI, AKS, Container Apps): Portable and scalable deployments
* Azure Functions (Serverless): Event-driven execution without infrastructure management

For example, a startup building a simple web app may choose Azure App Service for ease of deployment, while a large enterprise might use AKS for microservices architecture.

A real-life use case is a company migrating from on-premise servers. They might start with VMs (lift-and-shift), then gradually move to App Services or containers for better scalability.

Another example is an IoT system using Azure Functions for processing event data in real-time.

Choosing the right hosting option depends on control, scalability, cost, and complexity requirements.
